§ 4. Public law ‘in sacris, in sacerdotibus, in magistratibus consistit' Dig. 1. 1. 1. 2. ln the Roman view it comprised two parts: (1) constitu- tional law in its widest sense, i.e. the law which determines in whom the sovereign power shall reside, how it shall be exercised, and to what checks the persons among whom it may be distributed shall be subject. lt thus embraces all administrative law, which indeed under the later Empire formed its largest portion ; see the account os Theodosius’ Code in the General Introduction, p. 62, supr. Another important portion oi it was the ius sacrum, even after Constantine had made Christianity the national religion. (2) Crimina} law: privata delicta (torts) were distin- guished from publica delicta or crimes: ‘publica crimina, quorum delatio omnibus conceditur’ Cod. p 9. 30. pr, see Bk. iv. 18. 1. ins.

lt is os course impossible to draw a persectly hard and fast line be· tween public and private law, and this was ior historical reasons par· ticularly true of Rome (General Introd. p. 16 sq., supr.) ; manyinstitutions are from one point of view regarded as publici, from another as privati iuris; thus tutela, though discussed in the Institutas, was a munus pub- licum, and so in Dig. 28. 1. 3, it is said ‘testamenti factio publici iuris est' Civil procedure, from the prominente with which it is treated in Bk. iv, and also by Gaius, was apparently considered a part ol private law ; but by many this is regarded as arbitrary and unjustifiable, on the ground that rules of procedure are properly rules determining how the powers ol certain officers (magistrates and judges) shall be exercised.
